{"author":"Joe Oakhart","author_email":"joeoakhart+bot@navapbc.com","author_id":"594c-9dcf-5ad6-4e6d","data":{"fields":{"description":"# Enforce release-source authorization + version lockstep before publication\n\nRe-anchor the release to the proven OSS pattern: initiate it from the protected\n`main` branch via `workflow_dispatch` (so the source is reviewed-and-landed **by\nconstruction**), assert version-lockstep before build (pydantic's pre-build version\ncheck), and gate production publication on a required-reviewers environment (uv's\nrelease-gate + PyPA Trusted Publishing). (Readiness Finding 1 â€” verified VALID\nagainst `release.yml:17-21`, `infra/terraform-github/main.tf:23-101`,\n`docs/releasing.md`.)\n\n## Why\n\n`main` is constrained to the Gerrit replication deploy key, but `refs/tags/v*` was\ndeliberately left open (`infra/terraform-github/main.tf:23-28`) so a human can push\na `v*` tag to drive PyPI + MCP-registry + GitHub-Release publication\n(`release.yml:17-21`, jobs `build`/`publish`/`github_release`/`mcp_registry`). The\nonly gate anywhere is `if: github.event_name == 'push' && startsWith(github.ref,\n'refs/tags/v')` (release.yml:53/81/116) â€” nothing checks that the tagged SHA is an\nancestor of (or equal to) reviewed `main`, verifies any Gerrit/CI result for that\nexact SHA, or asserts version consistency. A PEP 740\nattestation would correctly name this repo's workflow but cannot distinguish a tag\non reviewed `main` from a tag on any other commit. Separately, the three version\nvalues (`pyproject.toml:10`, `server.json` top-level and `packages[].version`) are\nkept in lockstep only by a manual runbook (`docs/releasing.md`), so a future\nmismatch would publish disagreeing versions across the PyPI / GitHub-Release / MCP\nchannels with no machine check.\n\n## What\n\nAdopt uv's proven release process and pydantic's pre-build version check, in this\norder of control strength:\n\n- **Primary control â€” initiate from `main` via `workflow_dispatch` (source reviewed\n  by construction).** Make `workflow_dispatch` the sanctioned release trigger, run\n  from the `main` ref. Because the GitHub mirror's `main` is exactly the\n  Gerrit-reviewed-and-landed history, releasing from `main` guarantees the source is\n  reviewed **by construction** â€” the same guarantee the wider OSS world gets from\n  \"release only from the protected branch.\" This replaces \"accept whatever commit an\n  arbitrary pushed tag points at,\" which was the actual divergence from consensus.\n- **Version-lockstep, before build (pydantic pattern).** A first job parses the\n  intended version and every manifest and asserts exact equality **before build**:\n  `version_input == project.version == server.json.version ==\n  each server.json.packages[].version`; mismatch fails before build.\n- **Two-phase flow (preserves the existing `pypi` environment restriction).** GitHub\n  evaluates an environment's deployment-branch/tag policy against the **triggering\n  ref**, and the `pypi` environment is deliberately restricted to `v*` tags\n  (`docs/releasing.md:25`). So the dispatch job does **not** publish directly (a\n  dispatch ref is `refs/heads/main`, which the environment would block). Instead:\n  1. the **`workflow_dispatch` job** (from `main`) runs version-lockstep + the\n     ancestry assertion, then **creates and pushes the `v*` tag** and ends;\n  2. that **workflow-created `v*` tag push** triggers the existing build + publish\n     jobs, which run in the `v*` tag context â€” so the `pypi` environment's `v*`\n     restriction is satisfied and **kept unchanged** (it's a deliberate defense, not\n     something to widen).\n- **Human authorization â€” required-reviewers environment (uv release-gate + PyPA\n  Trusted Publishing).** `publish` depends on the `pypi` deployment environment with\n  required reviewers, so production publication needs a second human's approval. This\n  + release-initiated-from-`main` are the load-bearing controls â€” the mainstream OSS\n  pattern. (`build`/`publish`/`github_release`/`mcp_registry` stay tag-triggered, i.e.\n  keep their `if: github.event_name == 'push' && startsWith(github.ref, 'refs/tags/v')`\n  guards; the tag they run on is now the validated, workflow-created one.)\n- **Ancestry assertion (validated before the tag is created + fallback guard).** The\n  dispatch job asserts the release SHA is reachable from `origin/main` via\n  `git merge-base --is-ancestor \"$GITHUB_SHA\" origin/main` (checkout with\n  `fetch-depth: 0` + `git fetch origin main`, since a shallow clone defeats ancestry â€”\n  the repo documents this at `reconcile-bridge.yml:83-88` and `verify-identity.yaml`\n  already uses `fetch-depth: 0`) **before** creating the tag. The existing raw `v*`\n  tag-push path is retained as a fallback but runs the **same** ancestry assertion, so\n  a stray/hand-pushed tag on a non-`main` commit fails before build and can never\n  bypass the gate.\n- **Testing safely.** Exercise the deliberate-version-mismatch and non-ancestor-tag\n  failure paths against a staging repo / TestPyPI (or a dry-run publish target), never\n  the production PyPI/MCP registry, so the negative tests produce no real publication.\n- **Tag-push restriction stays OUT of scope (unchanged, deliberate).** `main.tf:23-28`\n  documents that the `tag_lock` resource was removed because GitHub offers **no viable\n  bypass actor** for tag writes in this mirror topology, and the contract test\n  `tests/unit/test_mirror_lock_terraform.py::test_module_is_main_only_no_tag_lock`\n  codifies \"no tag lock\". We do not restrict *who* can push a tag; the\n  release-from-`main` + environment-approval + ancestry controls make it unnecessary.\n- Record the approved SHA, tag, manifest versions, and artifact hashes in release\n  evidence (a job summary / uploaded evidence file).\n\n## Scope\n\n- `.github/workflows/release.yml` â€” add a `workflow_dispatch` trigger with a version\n  input (release from `main`); a `version-check` job (lockstep assertion, before\n  build); a tag-creation step after checks pass; `build`/`publish` gated on the check\n  job + the required-reviewers `pypi` environment; keep the `v*` tag trigger as a\n  gated fallback with the ancestry assertion.\n- `infra/terraform-github/main.tf` â€” **no change** (the deliberate no-tag-lock\n  decision and its contract test stand; see the out-of-scope rationale above).\n- `docs/releasing.md` â€” document the dispatch-from-`main` process, the version-lockstep\n  invariant, and the required environment reviewers. **Section ownership:** this story\n  owns the \"Release-source authorization\" section; Finding 3 owns the \"Build-once\"\n  section and Finding 4 owns the \"Pinning\" section, so the three concurrent release\n  stories do not overlap-edit the same headings.\n- Out of scope: the build-once / pinning work (Findings 3 and 4 â€” separate stories\n  that also touch `release.yml`; coordinate ordering per the epic).\n\n## Acceptance Criteria\n\n- [ ] The release is initiated by `workflow_dispatch` (a version input) and the\n  dispatch job enforces it runs from `main` (fails if `github.ref != 'refs/heads/main'`),\n  so the released source is reviewed-and-landed `main` by construction â€” verified by\n  the workflow definition and a run dispatched from a non-`main` ref failing the guard.\n- [ ] A `version-check` step in the dispatch job asserts `version_input`,\n  `pyproject.toml` version, `server.json` version, and every\n  `server.json.packages[].version` are equal and fails before creating the tag on any\n  mismatch â€” verified (against a staging/TestPyPI target, never production) by a run\n  where the values deliberately disagree, which exits before the tag is created with a\n  message naming each mismatched source.\n- [ ] The dispatch job creates and pushes the `v*` tag only after the version-lockstep\n  and ancestry checks pass; that workflow-created tag push is what triggers\n  `build`/`publish`/`github_release`/`mcp_registry` (which keep their existing\n  `if: github.event_name == 'push' && startsWith(github.ref, 'refs/tags/v')` guards),\n  so `publish` runs in the `v*` tag context and the `pypi` environment's existing\n  `v*`-tag restriction is preserved unchanged.\n- [ ] The ancestry assertion (`git merge-base --is-ancestor`, checkout `fetch-depth: 0`\n  + `git fetch origin main`) runs in the dispatch job before tag creation AND on the\n  retained raw `v*` tag-push fallback â€” verified (staging target) by a tag on a\n  non-ancestor commit failing before any build/publish job, and a tag on a non-tip\n  ancestor passing (proving no shallow-clone false-negative).\n- [ ] Publication safety does not depend on restricting tag-push identity: the story\n  documents that release-from-`main` + the required-reviewers `pypi` environment are\n  the load-bearing controls, and `infra/terraform-github/main.tf` is left unchanged\n  (the no-tag-lock contract test still passes).\n- [ ] `docs/releasing.md` documents the dispatch-from-`main` process, the\n  version-lockstep invariant, and the environment-reviewer requirement.\n- [ ] [operator-attested] The live `pypi` GitHub environment has required reviewers\n  enabled so production publication needs an independent approval (attested by a\n  comment naming the environment settings screenshot/URL or an org-admin confirmation).\n- [ ] `make lint && make typecheck && make test` pass, and the change lands via the\n  Gerrit two-vote gate."}},"env_id":"ade0f2ef-51cc-45a2-bb97-c09846cd3df5","event_type":"EDIT","timestamp":1784061053867328001,"uuid":"0de135d0-0963-49b8-b114-bb3ff7ffa048"}